\begin_layout Standard
We capture the generalisation of objects that transform this way by the
 following definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tensors
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An object that transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{\prime i_{1}\dots i_{p}}{}_{g_{1}\dots g_{q}}(\vec{x}')=\partial_{k_{1}}x^{\prime i_{1}}\dots\partial_{k_{p}}x^{\prime i_{p}}.\partial'_{g_{1}}x^{l_{1}}\dots\partial'_{g_{q}}x^{l_{q}}C^{k_{1}\dots k_{p}}{}_{l_{1}\dots l_{q}}(\vec{x})
\]

\end_inset

will be termed a rank 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)$
\end_inset

 tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Scalars, Contravariant and Covariant vectors
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A rank
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(0,0) tensor is called a scalar
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(1,0) tensor is called a contravariant vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(0,1) tensor is called a covariant vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some observations: Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{i_{1}\dots i_{p}}{}_{j_{1}\dots j_{q}}B^{k_{1}\dots k_{r}}{}_{l_{1}\dots l_{S}}$
\end_inset

 transforms as a 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+r,q+s)$
\end_inset

 tensor.
 Note also that for consistency 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{i_{1}}{}_{i_{1}}$
\end_inset

 should behave as a scalar.
 This follows directly from the transformation law and chain rule as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A^{\prime i_{1}}{}_{i_{1}} & =\underbrace{\partial_{k_{1}}x^{\prime i_{1}}\partial'_{i_{1}}}x^{l_{1}}A^{k_{1}}{}_{l_{1}}\\
 & =\delta_{k_{1}}^{l_{1}}A^{k_{1}}{}_{l_{1}}=A^{l_{1}}{}_{l_{1}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Understanding the Metric: Christophel Symbol, Reimann Tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We try to extract all essential information about the space as described
 by the metric.
 The main source of redundancy here is the freedom in choosing the coordinate
 system.
 Let us proceed systematically with first simplifying the metric itself.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=g_{ji}$
\end_inset

 and because we restrict ourselves to real numbers, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 can always be diagonalised by an appropriate orthogonal matrix transformation
 (at a given point of course).
 However, one is not restricted to orthogonal matrices in this case (the
 transformation doesn't have to preserve distances) and so one can do better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Take a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and assume its coordinate is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 in some coordinate system.
 Then, there exists a coordinate transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\to\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}(\vec{x}_{0})\to g'_{ij}(\vec{x}_{0}')=\text{diag}\{\pm,\dots,\pm,\pm\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof is straight forward as we shall see.
 It is interesting to note that for every continuous metric
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
one that changes only a little when the coordinate is changed a little,
 roughly speaking
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will have a fixed number of 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 entries throughout because otherwise there would have to be a jump for
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 to turn into a 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 (which is forbidden by the continuity assumption).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following expansion will be used several times in this sub-section.
 Consider a point denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'_{0}$
\end_inset

 by two coordinate systems which are related by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=f^{i}(\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

.
 I wish to write an expression for a point near 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 which I can write as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{i}=f^{i}(\vec{x}_{0}'+(\vec{x}'-\vec{x}_{0}'))=\cancelto{x_{0}^{i}}{f^{i}(\vec{x}_{0}')}+A^{i}{}_{j}(x^{\prime j}-x_{0}^{\prime j})+B^{i}{}_{jk}(x^{\prime j}-x_{0}^{\prime j})(x^{\prime k}-x_{0}^{\prime k})+\dots
\]

\end_inset

where we used the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}'$
\end_inset

 represent the same point.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{i}{}_{j}=\partial'_{j}f^{i}(x')|_{\vec{x}'=\vec{x}_{0}'}=\partial'_{j}x^{i}|_{\vec{x}'=\vec{x}_{0}'}$
\end_inset

 and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{i}{}_{jk}$
\end_inset

 would consist of two derivatives and so on.
\end_layout

